00:36:00.480 --> 00:36:06.640
and to what extent do they need
to be specialized early on?

00:36:06.640 --> 00:36:13.300
It sounded like Coach had sort
of a service dog background

00:36:13.300 --> 00:36:16.710
and then was trained in
particular skills that

00:36:16.710 --> 00:36:19.810
are valuable here.

00:36:19.810 --> 00:36:22.846
Say more about the training,
because it's a huge project.

00:36:22.846 --> 00:36:23.880
STEFANY SHAHEEN: Sure.

00:36:23.880 --> 00:36:25.546
We actually had the
privilege of meeting

00:36:25.546 --> 00:36:28.020
the person who developed the
training protocol for diabetes

00:36:28.020 --> 00:36:28.990
alert dogs.

00:36:28.990 --> 00:36:31.700
He himself was a dog trainer
for search and rescue

00:36:31.700 --> 00:36:34.730
and narcotic detection, and
he was also living with type

00:36:34.730 --> 00:36:35.380
I diabetes.

00:36:35.380 --> 00:36:38.100
And what he discovered was
that the dogs could pick up

00:36:38.100 --> 00:36:39.690
on the scent when
he was low or high,

00:36:39.690 --> 00:36:43.070
and so he developed a
protocol that is used now

00:36:43.070 --> 00:36:44.710
and was used to train Coach.

00:36:44.710 --> 00:36:47.610
The pipeline-- part of why
we wanted to share our story

00:36:47.610 --> 00:36:49.220
was that the single
biggest barrier

00:36:49.220 --> 00:36:51.730
to getting more
dogs more affordably

00:36:51.730 --> 00:36:55.430
available to families is the
availability of trainers.

00:36:55.430 --> 00:36:59.350
So there are-- the puppies
are not the problem.

00:36:59.350 --> 00:37:02.040
It's the number of trainers
who are able to train.

00:37:02.040 --> 00:37:05.090
And the way that
CARES works, they

00:37:05.090 --> 00:37:11.014
don't breed dogs and
let the puppies wait.

00:37:11.014 --> 00:37:12.430
They breed the
dogs and the timing

00:37:12.430 --> 00:37:14.304
of the puppies being
born coincides with when

00:37:14.304 --> 00:37:15.780
a trainer is available.

00:37:15.780 --> 00:37:21.420
So as soon as the puppy's born,
they are studied and evaluated

00:37:21.420 --> 00:37:22.980
to see, are these
dogs going to be

00:37:22.980 --> 00:37:24.630
ready to do what
they need to do?

00:37:24.630 --> 00:37:28.380
So some dogs don't mate
it through the training.

00:37:28.380 --> 00:37:30.110
In fact, we were
joking that we want

00:37:30.110 --> 00:37:31.980
to be on the list
for the dropout dogs,

00:37:31.980 --> 00:37:33.800
because when Elle and
Coach go to college,

00:37:33.800 --> 00:37:37.900
we're going to need
another dog in the house.

00:37:37.900 --> 00:37:42.770
And there are PTSD,
seizure detection, diabetes

00:37:42.770 --> 00:37:45.550
alert-- CARES doesn't do
this, but there are also

00:37:45.550 --> 00:37:48.690
dogs now being trained
in cancer detection.

00:37:48.690 --> 00:37:51.590
And so what CARES
would explain is

00:37:51.590 --> 00:37:55.580
that based on what they
see the dog's abilities,

00:37:55.580 --> 00:37:59.850
they would be either funneled
into diabetes alert or seizure

00:37:59.850 --> 00:38:02.180
detection or PTSD.

00:38:02.180 --> 00:38:04.550
They also are particular
about which breeds

00:38:04.550 --> 00:38:05.650
get trained for what.

00:38:05.650 --> 00:38:10.240
So often you're talking about
German shepherds for veterans,

00:38:10.240 --> 00:38:13.260
especially, who are
getting dogs for PTSD,

00:38:13.260 --> 00:38:15.210
and that's because
the breed is such

00:38:15.210 --> 00:38:18.580
that they're more
intimidating, and their job

00:38:18.580 --> 00:38:22.100
is to protect the perimeter of
a veteran or somebody coping

00:38:22.100 --> 00:38:23.190
with PTSD.

00:38:23.190 --> 00:38:26.850
And in fact, there were
multiple veterans in Elle class

00:38:26.850 --> 00:38:31.930
who were there for a
dog to help treat PTSD.

00:38:31.930 --> 00:38:33.830
They use labs and
golden retrievers

00:38:33.830 --> 00:38:36.920
predominantly for seizure
detection and diabetes alert,

00:38:36.920 --> 00:38:39.270
especially in young
people, because they're

00:38:39.270 --> 00:38:43.020
in situations where the dogs
have to be especially social.

00:38:43.020 --> 00:38:45.440
And they say it's
about 2,000 hours,

00:38:45.440 --> 00:38:48.800
but Elle works with
Coach every day

00:38:48.800 --> 00:38:50.876
in order to help
him be successful.

00:38:50.876 --> 00:38:52.750
Do you want to share
like the kinds of things

00:38:52.750 --> 00:38:54.980
you do every day?

00:38:54.980 --> 00:38:57.080
ELLE: He needs to
stay very regimented,

00:38:57.080 --> 00:39:01.970
so he stays on a very specific
schedule in terms of feeding

00:39:01.970 --> 00:39:04.720
and when I walk him
and stuff like that.

00:39:04.720 --> 00:39:07.830
But I also have to
groom him once a week.

00:39:07.830 --> 00:39:11.220
And I take him on
training walks just

00:39:11.220 --> 00:39:14.440
to make sure that
he is up to date

00:39:14.440 --> 00:39:18.670
and still alert at
all times of the day.

00:39:18.670 --> 00:39:21.340
STEFANY SHAHEEN: We had
an interesting dilemma.

00:39:21.340 --> 00:39:23.530
That summer where I showed
you that photo where

00:39:23.530 --> 00:39:25.310
they were both
asleep in the car,

00:39:25.310 --> 00:39:27.870
he was having trouble waking
up in the middle of the night.

00:39:27.870 --> 00:39:31.982
And there were a couple times
where she was just below range

00:39:31.982 --> 00:39:34.440
when he should have been awake
and alerting, and he wasn't.

00:39:34.440 --> 00:39:36.141
And I called the
trainer and I said,

00:39:36.141 --> 00:39:37.390
I don't know what's happening.

00:39:37.390 --> 00:39:40.116
And she said, well, describe
what the day is like.

00:39:40.116 --> 00:39:41.865
I said, well, they
leave the house at 6:30

00:39:41.865 --> 00:39:43.950
and they're in this
summer program all day,

00:39:43.950 --> 00:39:45.780
and then he's getting
home at 7:30 at night

00:39:45.780 --> 00:39:47.300
and we take him for his walk.

00:39:47.300 --> 00:39:48.770
And she said, he's exhausted.

00:39:51.330 --> 00:39:53.360
He's working overtime
and he needs a break.

00:39:53.360 --> 00:39:57.370
So we have to build in
specified sleep time

00:39:57.370 --> 00:39:59.240
where he can sleep
and know she's OK

00:39:59.240 --> 00:40:02.070
and he's sort of off
the clock, not working.

00:40:02.070 --> 00:40:04.970
We also often get the
question about play.

00:40:04.970 --> 00:40:07.770
Can he ever just be a dog,
or is he always working?

00:40:07.770 --> 00:40:11.700
And what we've learned is that
you have to distinguish play

00:40:11.700 --> 00:40:12.780
as a reward.

00:40:12.780 --> 00:40:15.510
So he gets to play when he's
done what he's supposed to do.

00:40:15.510 --> 00:40:17.260
And then you distinguish
play from work

00:40:17.260 --> 00:40:19.940
by taking the vest off,
taking the working collar off

00:40:19.940 --> 00:40:21.640
and putting the play collar on.

00:40:21.640 --> 00:40:23.940
So you'll often see
him outside, if he's

00:40:23.940 --> 00:40:26.834
being rewarded with fetch
or some kind of play,

00:40:26.834 --> 00:40:28.000
he doesn't have his vest on.

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:29.880
He's got his play collar on.

00:40:29.880 --> 00:40:32.140
But he also is
really wired to work.

00:40:32.140 --> 00:40:34.930
So whenever they're
separated for any reason,

00:40:34.930 --> 00:40:37.980
he's very unsettled, because
he is looking for a job to do.

00:40:37.980 --> 00:40:41.356
I remember the very first
time they were separated,

00:40:41.356 --> 00:40:42.730
she went to the
mall with friends

00:40:42.730 --> 00:40:44.563
and there was not room
in the car for Coach.

00:40:44.563 --> 00:40:47.342
And they'd been together
nonstop for four weeks.

00:40:47.342 --> 00:40:48.800
And the trainer
said, they're going

00:40:48.800 --> 00:40:51.307
to have to get comfortable not
being together all the time,

00:40:51.307 --> 00:40:52.890
because inevitably
there will be times

00:40:52.890 --> 00:40:54.710
when they're not together.

00:40:54.710 --> 00:40:57.822
So she left the house crying.

00:40:57.822 --> 00:41:01.190
As she's leaving, his nose
is pressed against the glass,

00:41:01.190 --> 00:41:02.610
and then he was very agitated.

00:41:02.610 --> 00:41:04.090
And she said, well, he's
was looking for a job to do.

00:41:04.090 --> 00:41:04.965
Give him a job to do.

00:41:04.965 --> 00:41:07.510
So we put the laundry basket
in the middle of the kitchen

00:41:07.510 --> 00:41:09.640
floor, and he would walk
around the kids' bedrooms,

00:41:09.640 --> 00:41:12.280
pick up the stuffed animals,
put them in the laundry basket,

00:41:12.280 --> 00:41:14.126
get a reward.

00:41:14.126 --> 00:41:15.500
So he is very much
a working dog.

00:41:15.500 --> 00:41:18.392
He needs to work, and he
needs to stay regimented.

00:41:18.392 --> 00:41:19.850
He goes to the
bathroom on command.

00:41:19.850 --> 00:41:21.312
People often say,
how do you know

00:41:21.312 --> 00:41:23.270
if he's alerting versus
just trying to tell you

00:41:23.270 --> 00:41:24.522
he needs to go out?

00:41:24.522 --> 00:41:26.980
He doesn't tell you he needs
to go out, because he goes out

00:41:26.980 --> 00:41:28.680
when he is supposed
to go out, and he

00:41:28.680 --> 00:41:32.440
goes to the bathroom on
command, and not otherwise.

00:41:32.440 --> 00:41:34.519
Yeah, it's amazing.

00:41:34.519 --> 00:41:36.060
AUDIENCE: And early
on, you mentioned

00:41:36.060 --> 00:41:40.490
when you were first
investigating service dogs,

00:41:40.490 --> 00:41:44.340
that it was-- you were surprised
at how unregulated it was.

00:41:44.340 --> 00:41:50.900
Now, in retrospect, do you think
that there's a need for more?

00:41:50.900 --> 00:41:52.210
Would that be helpful?

00:41:52.210 --> 00:41:54.510
What's your sense of
what could be done

00:41:54.510 --> 00:41:55.900
that would be useful there?

00:41:55.900 --> 00:41:59.170
STEFANY SHAHEEN: Yeah, I
have to say diabetes alert

00:41:59.170 --> 00:42:00.810
dogs are still very unusual.

00:42:00.810 --> 00:42:02.520
There aren't that many.

00:42:02.520 --> 00:42:04.790
CARES, which has been in
operation for 10 years,

00:42:04.790 --> 00:42:07.690
has only trained 1,300
dogs total, and not

00:42:07.690 --> 00:42:10.100
just for diabetes alert.

00:42:10.100 --> 00:42:13.860
It's a new and emerging area.

00:42:13.860 --> 00:42:17.280
And I think we need
better research that

00:42:17.280 --> 00:42:21.060
actually demonstrates the effect
these animals can have, not

00:42:21.060 --> 00:42:23.360
just from a
biometric standpoint,

00:42:23.360 --> 00:42:25.610
because actually, Elle's
A1C is better now than it

00:42:25.610 --> 00:42:28.010
was before we had Coach.

00:42:28.010 --> 00:42:31.250
So we could tell you that she
actually is in range more often

00:42:31.250 --> 00:42:33.880
and her body is healthier
than it was without him.

00:42:33.880 --> 00:42:37.860
But we need that quantified
in the form of research that's

00:42:37.860 --> 00:42:39.460
not just anecdotal.

00:42:39.460 --> 00:42:41.260
But beyond that, I
think the industry

00:42:41.260 --> 00:42:42.750
itself is very poorly regulated.

00:42:46.200 --> 00:42:49.440
We've met too many families who
have spent an inordinate amount

00:42:49.440 --> 00:42:51.760
of money, I mean tens
of thousands of dollars,

00:42:51.760 --> 00:42:54.460
have raised money through
philanthropic efforts

00:42:54.460 --> 00:42:57.560
to get a dog, and the dog
comes and doesn't work.

00:42:57.560 --> 00:43:00.240
So there needs to be a
national accreditation

00:43:00.240 --> 00:43:02.520
process that is the standard.

00:43:02.520 --> 00:43:05.940
CARES works with one and
abides by it very carefully,

00:43:05.940 --> 00:43:07.550
but there are others that don't.

00:43:07.550 --> 00:43:12.040
And ultimately, right
now, Coach and Elle

00:43:12.040 --> 00:43:14.530
are protected through
the ADA, because they're

00:43:14.530 --> 00:43:18.660
a trained service team and
he has a demonstrated job.

00:43:18.660 --> 00:43:21.680
But how many of you have been on
an airplane with a service dog,

00:43:21.680 --> 00:43:22.480
right?

00:43:22.480 --> 00:43:26.860
So there's also this--
it's a very gray area,

00:43:26.860 --> 00:43:28.880
and we need to tighten
it up, because it

00:43:28.880 --> 00:43:32.030
will help the people who really
are in need of a service dog,

00:43:32.030 --> 00:43:34.050
and it will help
the families who

00:43:34.050 --> 00:43:36.490
are trying to navigate their
way through this process

00:43:36.490 --> 00:43:37.880
and have some assurance.

00:43:37.880 --> 00:43:41.600
I mean, CARES has said to
me, they hear from families

00:43:41.600 --> 00:43:46.975
all the time who spent $25,000
and got a dog that didn't work.

00:43:46.975 --> 00:43:49.890
And that's just not right.

00:43:49.890 --> 00:43:51.560
AUDIENCE: This is a
question for Elle.

00:43:51.560 --> 00:43:54.000
Since you started at
school, how have you

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:56.980
found that the school
environment, or maybe even just

00:43:56.980 --> 00:43:59.230
the way your friends think
about these types of issues

00:43:59.230 --> 00:44:00.490
have changed, because
you've been living with it,

00:44:00.490 --> 00:44:02.656
but have you seen changes
come about in your school,

00:44:02.656 --> 00:44:04.700
or your friends are more
interested in talking

00:44:04.700 --> 00:44:08.060
about medical research?

00:44:08.060 --> 00:44:10.250
ELLE: Not necessarily.

00:44:10.250 --> 00:44:16.050
He-- like my mom said before,
I don't really classify myself

00:44:16.050 --> 00:44:18.280
as a diabetic, so
it's not something

00:44:18.280 --> 00:44:20.410
I talk about very often.

00:44:20.410 --> 00:44:23.310
It's just sort of a
part of my daily life.

00:44:23.310 --> 00:44:28.580
So when I got Coach,
especially as a freshman going

00:44:28.580 --> 00:44:30.550
into this very large
school and trying

00:44:30.550 --> 00:44:36.840
to navigate social aspects of
high school, that was hard,

00:44:36.840 --> 00:44:40.140
because I was-- I
felt at the beginning,

00:44:40.140 --> 00:44:44.030
before I even got Coach, that he
might be putting a label on me,

00:44:44.030 --> 00:44:48.580
or just a label that something
might be wrong with me.

00:44:48.580 --> 00:44:52.060
But then I got to school,
and they loved him.

00:44:52.060 --> 00:44:55.470
He really became a part
of the school community,

00:44:55.470 --> 00:44:59.310
and everyone welcomed
him with open arms.

00:44:59.310 --> 00:45:02.620
My freshman English class,
they had tennis balls

00:45:02.620 --> 00:45:04.620
on the bottom of our
chairs, and he would always

00:45:04.620 --> 00:45:06.460
try to bite them off.

00:45:06.460 --> 00:45:08.540
So the next day,
my English teacher

00:45:08.540 --> 00:45:10.900
brought in a bucket
of old tennis balls

00:45:10.900 --> 00:45:12.516
for him to chew on during class.

00:45:12.516 --> 00:45:13.890
STEFANY SHAHEEN:
Which she wasn't

00:45:13.890 --> 00:45:15.474
supposed to do, by the way.

00:45:15.474 --> 00:45:16.390
ELLE: It was a reward.

00:45:16.390 --> 00:45:18.290
STEFANY SHAHEEN: I know.

00:45:18.290 --> 00:45:20.790
ELLE: But he's really become a
part of the school community.

00:45:20.790 --> 00:45:26.580
But in terms of diabetes
being a conversation topic,

00:45:26.580 --> 00:45:31.360
I don't think that
has changed as much.

00:45:31.360 --> 00:45:33.450
But I'm willing to talk
about it with anyone

00:45:33.450 --> 00:45:35.210
who has questions about it.

00:45:35.210 --> 00:45:37.090
STEFANY SHAHEEN: What
we have discovered

00:45:37.090 --> 00:45:41.595
is that without Coach, the
topic of diabetes is very heavy,

00:45:41.595 --> 00:45:43.970
because you're trying to
explain the reality of what it's

00:45:43.970 --> 00:45:46.240
like to live with
a chronic disease,

00:45:46.240 --> 00:45:49.370
and what it means that you
can't go to sleep and trust

00:45:49.370 --> 00:45:52.020
that you're safe
through the night.

00:45:52.020 --> 00:45:54.990
But with Coach, it allows us to
have conversations with people

00:45:54.990 --> 00:45:57.330
who are really fascinated
by how Coach works

00:45:57.330 --> 00:46:00.920
and what he does for Elle, that
open the door to information

00:46:00.920 --> 00:46:03.920
and education about what it's
like to live with diabetes.

00:46:03.920 --> 00:46:06.090
And I think that's
been very empowering.

00:46:06.090 --> 00:46:07.840
And part of the reason
we share the story,

00:46:07.840 --> 00:46:10.530
we really wrestled with, do
we want to write this book?

00:46:10.530 --> 00:46:12.470
Do we really want
to tell the story?

00:46:12.470 --> 00:46:14.405
And I remember a
conversation Elle

00:46:14.405 --> 00:46:16.857
and I had, because I felt like
it was up to her to decide.

00:46:16.857 --> 00:46:19.440
I was willing to do the work if
she was willing to put herself

00:46:19.440 --> 00:46:20.330
out there.

00:46:20.330 --> 00:46:24.710
And you answer so many
questions about, well,

00:46:24.710 --> 00:46:26.660
is it what you ate that
caused your diabetes?

00:46:26.660 --> 00:46:30.290
Is it because you
didn't exercise enough,

00:46:30.290 --> 00:46:33.050
the confusion between type II
diabetes and type I diabetes,

00:46:33.050 --> 00:46:35.870
and lots of people who have
asked her if she's just

00:46:35.870 --> 00:46:38.190
training Coach, or
wave their hands

00:46:38.190 --> 00:46:40.070
in front of her face
to see if she needs--

00:46:40.070 --> 00:46:41.910
if he's a seeing-eye dog.

00:46:41.910 --> 00:46:46.020
So for all those reasons, she
wanted to share the story.

00:46:46.020 --> 00:46:48.770
And I think it's been very
empowering in that way,

00:46:48.770 --> 00:46:53.180
because it allows us to open
up about life before Coach

00:46:53.180 --> 00:46:56.170
and the risks that Elle lives
with every day with Coach

00:46:56.170 --> 00:46:58.430
in a way that I think
without him is a much

00:46:58.430 --> 00:47:00.720
harder conversation to have.

00:47:00.720 --> 00:47:02.087
So that's been wonderful.

00:47:02.087 --> 00:47:04.420
AUDIENCE: And then just one
quick follow up-- how has he

00:47:04.420 --> 00:47:06.030
taken to music and theater?

00:47:06.030 --> 00:47:07.970
Does he have any
kind of-- express

00:47:07.970 --> 00:47:11.480
any preference or, he just
has to wait quietly backstage?

00:47:11.480 --> 00:47:13.300
ELLE: He loves it.

00:47:13.300 --> 00:47:16.850
He likes it more-- my younger
sister plays volleyball

00:47:16.850 --> 00:47:19.630
and my brother plays
baseball and soccer.

00:47:19.630 --> 00:47:22.660
And he hates the
noises at the game.

00:47:22.660 --> 00:47:25.600
But he loves coming
to rehearsal.

00:47:25.600 --> 00:47:28.350
And within a year
of me getting him,

00:47:28.350 --> 00:47:32.076
I was doing a summer
program, and they actually

00:47:32.076 --> 00:47:33.450
wrote a part for
him in the show,

00:47:33.450 --> 00:47:37.490
and he had his own little
dressing room backstage.

00:47:37.490 --> 00:47:38.680
It was really cute.

00:47:38.680 --> 00:47:41.710
STEFANY SHAHEEN: And they
were both in "Of Mice and Men"

00:47:41.710 --> 00:47:43.840
with Boston Children's
Theater down here,

00:47:43.840 --> 00:47:47.020
and that was the worst
for me, because they

00:47:47.020 --> 00:47:49.000
both got killed in the play.

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:50.010
I said, OK, no more.

00:47:50.010 --> 00:47:52.300
Coach and Elle can't
have something bad

00:47:52.300 --> 00:47:54.350
happen in the play.

00:47:54.350 --> 00:47:55.760
But it's been amazing.

00:47:55.760 --> 00:47:58.690
And as Elle said, I think he
must have had whistle training

00:47:58.690 --> 00:48:01.192
at some point, because he
cannot handle-- I mean,

00:48:01.192 --> 00:48:04.185
he just does not like being in
the gym cheering on Anna with

00:48:04.185 --> 00:48:05.060
the referee whistles.

00:48:05.060 --> 00:48:07.030
It drives him crazy.

00:48:07.030 --> 00:48:09.220
We actually had,
and I'll share this,

00:48:09.220 --> 00:48:13.660
this is a very present
and pressing story for me.

00:48:13.660 --> 00:48:16.940
Elle just opened a
show a few weeks ago,

00:48:16.940 --> 00:48:19.670
and we hadn't figured out how
to handle performance nights

00:48:19.670 --> 00:48:23.320
with Coach, because there's no
way to keep him safe backstage

00:48:23.320 --> 00:48:26.310
and allow him to do his
job, because he would have

00:48:26.310 --> 00:48:29.402
to be crated, and then he'd
have to bark in order to alert,

00:48:29.402 --> 00:48:30.860
and so he'd be
barking in the show.

00:48:30.860 --> 00:48:33.220
And we've tried a
few different things,

00:48:33.220 --> 00:48:35.040
and it just doesn't work.

00:48:35.040 --> 00:48:38.920
So opening night, she was
running the show in rehearsal

00:48:38.920 --> 00:48:44.170
before the actual opening, and
didn't have a Coach with her,

00:48:44.170 --> 00:48:47.066
had had too much insulin for the
amount of dancing and activity

00:48:47.066 --> 00:48:48.940
she was doing in the
show and not enough food

00:48:48.940 --> 00:48:52.830
before the show with nerves,
and her continuous glucose

00:48:52.830 --> 00:48:54.541
monitor was alarming
her on her phone,

00:48:54.541 --> 00:48:56.040
but she couldn't
hear it because she

00:48:56.040 --> 00:48:58.050
was on the stage with
the music playing.

00:48:58.050 --> 00:49:00.940
Luckily, it was alarming
me on my phone at work,

00:49:00.940 --> 00:49:04.190
and I was incessantly
trying to reach her,

00:49:04.190 --> 00:49:06.460
couldn't reach her because
she's on the stage,

00:49:06.460 --> 00:49:08.290
was able to find someone
in the box office

00:49:08.290 --> 00:49:10.950
to go into the theater to
pull her off the stage,

00:49:10.950 --> 00:49:13.570
and it took us about two
hours of treating the low

00:49:13.570 --> 00:49:16.780
to get her into a healthy
range so she could perform.

00:49:16.780 --> 00:49:18.860
And I use that as an
example because it just

00:49:18.860 --> 00:49:21.542
happened a few weeks ago, and
the juxtaposition of what that

00:49:21.542 --> 00:49:23.000
would have looked
like with Coach--

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:24.740
so if that had happened
in a rehearsal and Coach

00:49:24.740 --> 00:49:26.406
was in the theater
in rehearsal, he just

00:49:26.406 --> 00:49:30.140
would have walked onto the
stage and made her stop,

00:49:30.140 --> 00:49:32.420
and made her very aware
of what was happening.

00:49:32.420 --> 00:49:35.880
And that's the value
of having him around,

00:49:35.880 --> 00:49:38.190
why we feel so lucky.

00:49:38.190 --> 00:49:41.230
One more question, anyone?

00:49:41.230 --> 00:49:42.790
Well, this has been such a gift.

00:49:42.790 --> 00:49:45.270
I can't thank you enough for
the chance to share our story,

00:49:45.270 --> 00:49:49.300
and we look forward to
coming back at a later time.

00:49:49.300 --> 00:49:53.317
[APPLAUSE]

